1. The Time Tool (datetime)

    Class: datetime
        Definition: A built-in tool to handle dates and times mathematically,
                    rather than treating them as plain text.

        Usage: The HTML form sends the date as raw text (a string). The database
                cannot process raw text as a date. The method datetime.strptime()
                is used to catch that text and translate it into a strict date format
                that the database can safely store.

2. The Web Engine (flask)

    Class: Flask
        Definition: The core software that turns a normal Python script into a live web server.

        Usage: Flask(__name__) starts the engine. The entire application runs inside this object.

    Object: request
        Definition: A container that holds all the information sent from the
                    web browser to the server.

        Usage: It acts as the receiver. request.method == "POST" checks if the form
                button was actually clicked. request.form["first_name"] reaches into the HTML
                and pulls out the exact text typed into that specific box.

    Function: render_template
        Definition: A command to load HTML files and send them to the screen.

        Usage: Placed at the very end to display index.html after the background code finishes running.

    Function: flash
        Definition: A tool used to send a temporary alert message from the backend to the frontend.

        Usage: It generates the "submitted successfully" text and passes it to the HTML.

3. The Database Translator (flask_sqlalchemy)

    Class: SQLAlchemy
        Definition: A tool that translates Python code into SQL commands. It allows the
        creation and management of databases without writing raw SQL queries.

        Usage: db = SQLAlchemy(app) links the web app to a local database file named data.db.

    Classes: db.Model, db.Column, db.String, db.Integer
        Definition: The architectural blueprints used to design a database table.

        Usage: Used to build the Form class. They strictly define what kind of data is
                allowed in each column (e.g., numbers for the ID, text strings for names, dates for the date column).

    Methods: db.session.add() & db.session.commit()
        Definition: The commands to insert new information into the database.

        Usage: add() places the newly collected form data into a temporary waiting area.
                commit() permanently saves that data into the actual database file.

    Method: db.create_all()
        Definition: An initialization command that generates the database tables.

        Usage: Runs right before the server starts. If the data.db file does not exist, this creates it automatically.

4. The Email Courier (flask_mail)

    Class: Mail
        Definition: The engine that connects the Python server to a real email provider (like Gmail).

        Usage: Mail(app) reads the SMTP server settings provided in the app.config block and establishes the connection.

    Class: Message
        Definition: A digital envelope used to format an email before sending.

        Usage: It is used to bundle the subject line, the sender address, the recipient address,
                and the actual text body (message_body) into one package.

    Method: mail.send()
        Definition: The trigger command.

        Usage: It takes the drafted Message package and pushes it out over the internet to the recipient's inbox.